<TYPE>
<P>
Wild Art 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA050690-0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 214603 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 6, 1990, Sunday, Bulldog Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 1; Column 1; Advance Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
517 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHEARING THE LAND; 
</P>
<P>
SHEEP CLEAR BUILDING SITE FOR DEVELOPER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN CLEMENTE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yesterday they were sheep. Today, to officials of a development company, they 
are "organic construction workers." 
</P>
<P>
But for the 2,000 sheep that arrived recently to feed on the rolling green 
hills east of San Clemente, it's all just another free lunch. 
</P>
<P>
Bleating as they cascaded down the ramps of 10 triple-decker semi-trucks, the 
sheep landed with gazelle-like bounds and headed for the tall grass and scrub 
brush they will clear to make way for 5,000 new homes. 
</P>
<P>
For the developer, Arvida Co., the arrangement means the free removal of tall 
grass and scrub brush that otherwise would have been graded by machine and 
shipped to a landfill. For the sheep rancher, Pedro Indocochea of Perris, it 
means a way to feed his herd. 
</P>
<P>
"We're putting the vegetation into the tummies of sheep instead of hauling it 
away," said Horst Schor, Arvida vice president. "And there won't be any 
pollutants released into the air. Environmentally, this is a good solution." 
</P>
<P>
Known as voracious eaters that will strip their grazing area of all vegetation, 
the sheep will save Arvida several thousand dollars, said company spokesman 
Kevin Canning. 
</P>
<P>
"They will basically eat about anything," said Dorine Indocochea, who keeps the 
books for her rancher husband. "They're real garbage disposals on legs." 
</P>
<P>
The 2,000-acre site of the Talega Valley housing project lies half in 
unincorporated county territory and half in the city of San Clemente. County 
officials have approved plans for up to 2,700 homes, and the San Clemente 
Planning Commission is considering plans for 2,300 more. 
</P>
<P>
Pedro Indocochea said he is happy that the Arvida Co. called him in April to 
propose the idea. 
</P>
<P>
With grazing lands becoming scarce in Southern California, Indocochea said he 
is glad to bear the $12,000 cost of trucking the sheep to Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
"Land development and environmentalists make it really hard to find anywhere 
for them to feed," he said. "I'm glad we're able to find them a home here." 
</P>
<P>
From Needles to Brawley, the flock has bounced around Southern California in 
search of grazeable land, Indocochea said. 
</P>
<P>
"About the only places left for them to eat now are the farmlands," he said. 
"And (farmers) know it and charge a lot for my sheep to use their lands." 
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, cattle from South County's sprawling ranchlands have been used 
to control scrub brush in the area. 
</P>
<P>
But sheep, say Arvida officials, are better natural lawn mowers than cows. 
</P>
<P>
"Cattle leave something like the bottom third of the plant," Canning said. 
"Sheep will get it all, right down to the roots." 
</P>
<P>
The partnership between sheep herder and developer is not unknown in the 
building industry, although Schor said it is the first time the arrangement has 
been tried in Orange County since he helped build the community of Anaheim 
Hills in the mid-1970s. 
</P>
<P>
"The sheep worked out really well back then," Schor said. "They'll do a great 
job here, too." 
</P>
<P>
The sheep, all 1-year-old female breeders, will live off the land here for at 
least three months. 
</P>
<P>
"Right now, it's beautiful here," Dorine Indocochea said. "I don't know how 
long it will last." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Some of the 2,000 voracious sheep fan out over a San Clemente hillside 
to dine on vegetation and in the process clear the land for a housing 
subdivision. ; Photo, Leaping sheep spend some time gamboling, but their 
expertise is in eating. DON KELSEN / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
