<HEADLINE>
<P>
A PARK IN THEORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I have been observing the progress of the San Dieguito River Valley Regional 
Park with great interest and frustration. 
</P>
<P>
This 43-mile, sea-to-mountain park from Del Mar to Julian is exciting and vital 
to preserve some of the stunning natural landscape of lagoon, wetland, valley, 
mountain diversity, which is rapidly disappearing. 
</P>
<P>
I hear about the park repeatedly in the press and from political persons as if 
it were a reality. However, the park exists only as a proposal. 
</P>
<P>
No land has, as yet, been acquired. Until land is in public ownership, it is 
not protected. 
</P>
<P>
The bureaucratic structure for the park is in place. There's the joint powers 
authority with representation from the six communities involved; there is a 
Citizens Advisory Committee. There is even $10 million available for land 
acquisition, but why hasn't it been spent? 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile land costs escalate, wetlands disappear -- 90% of the wetlands in 
California are already gone. 
</P>
<P>
The longer the delay, the higher the cost of acquisition and less will be 
purchased with funds available. 
</P>
<P>
Will this be a paper park or the real thing -- and when? 
</P>
<P>
SYLVIA TROY 
</P>
<P>
Del Mar 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
