<HEADLINE>
<P>
THEY REALLY WANT TO GROW UP TO BE RICH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dr. Joyce Brothers (April 24)) gives some fascinating explanations of why young 
people are motivated to enter various careers. She sees medicine as attractive 
to those interested in a "nurturing profession (where one) . . . can help 
others." 
</P>
<P>
Law is attractive to young people "who feel they were unfairly treated by 
adults." On the other hand, Dr. Brothers takes the position that teaching, and 
religious ministry, are attractive to those who "like to give orders and be 
seen as authorities." 
</P>
<P>
Get real, Joyce. Young people attracted to law and medicine are mostly drawn by 
the promise of big bucks; and the desire to help and nurture is stronger among 
those who go into teaching and the clergy. 
</P>
<P>
I imagine that Dr. Brothers would assert that young people are drawn to the 
profession of psychology because they believe that they will eat of the fruit 
of the Tree of Knowledge and become like gods. After reading her column, I 
think she could use a few more mouthfuls. 
</P>
<P>
LARRY SELK, Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
