<HEADLINE>
<P>
ENDING U.S. AID TO EL SALVADOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The editorial "El Salvador -- a Big Question" (April 17) goes a long way toward 
recognizing the futility and the immorality of U.S. intervention in El 
Salvador. Yet in the end it accepts the logic that has kept U.S. arms aid 
fueling the war for the last decade. 
</P>
<P>
"Without outside aid," you say, "El Salvador's war-ravaged economy would 
collapse." But for most Salvadorans, with the notable exception of the 
oligarchic and military elite, the economy already has collapsed. More than 
half the adult work force is unemployed, and living standards have plummeted. 
</P>
<P>
Against the aid cutoff proposed by several congressional leaders, you argue 
that such a move might tempt "leftist rebels to try and strike a knockout 
blow." But it is clearly the hard-line right in the government and the army, 
and not the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front (FMLN), that would prefer 
a military solution at this point. 
</P>
<P>
A cutoff of U.S. aid would help produce progress toward a negotiated political 
settlement, with concessions made by both sides. 
</P>
<P>
But even if, as seems unlikely, an aid cutoff were to bring about the outright 
collapse of the Cristiani govennment, its replacement would most likely be a 
coalition of all the democratic opposition forces on the center and left, 
including the Christian Democrats, the social democratic parties, and the FMLN. 
Such a reformist government would be a vast improvement over the nightmarish 
regime now in power. 
</P>
<P>
Until we back up our professed concern for human rights by halting all arms 
aid, the war will continue and the negotiations under way now in Geneva will 
achieve little. 
</P>
<P>
MICHAEL J. DAVIS 
</P>
<P>
Executive Director, El Salvador 
</P>
<P>
Institute for Democratic Development 
</P>
<P>
San Francisco 
</P>
