<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALBUM REVIEWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEONARD FEATHER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
**** 
</P>
<P>
MARCUS ROBERTS 
</P>
<P>
"Deep in the Shed", RCA Novus 
</P>
<P>
This is an all blues album, or so says pianist Roberts; it depends on how 
strictly one construes the term. What his writing (for a three- or four-horn 
band) gains in diversity of moods, modes and meters, it loses now and then in 
true blues soul. 
</P>
<P>
In fact, he has gone so deep into the woodshed that experimentation sometimes 
takes precedence over celebration. Still, it's an intriguing example of his 
evolution as a composer. Wessell Anderson's alto sax brings to "Nebuchadnezzar" 
the flavor of Ellington, or what Duke might be writing had he survived and 
advanced. "E. Dankworth" is a strong cut, thanks to the inventive trumpeter for 
whom it was named. 
</P>
<P>
 Albums are rated on a scale of one star (poor) to five stars (a classic). 
</P>
<P>
LEONARD FEATHER 
</P>
</TEXT>
