<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON, D.C.; 
</P>
<P>
CONTRACTOR ACCUSED OF HINDERING PROBE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rep. John D. Dingell (D-Mich.) charged that the manufacturer of the Navy's new 
$1.2-billion guided-missile destroyer is hampering congressional investigators 
examining allegations of contract fraud. Dingell, in a letter to Defense 
Secretary Dick Cheney, said Bath Iron Works of Bath, Me., has refused to 
provide the congressional General Accounting Office with documents or allow 
investigators to interview employees unless the GAO promises to withhold the 
information from Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA050690-0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 214904 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 6, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
