TRAINING; TRAINERS; HEART SURGERY 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA050690-0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 280382 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 6, 1990, Sunday, Bulldog Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<P>
ABEL R KIVIAT 
</P>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 1; Column 6; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
806 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
KIVIAT IS OLDEST LIVING MEDALIST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KEN MURRAY, BALTIMORE EVENING SUN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BALTIMORE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The most strenuous exercise Abel R. Kiviat gets these days is walking 200 feet 
to the mailbox and back at his Lakehurst, N.J., residence. The next most 
strenuous exercise he gets is the 150-foot, round-trip journey to the trash 
bin. 
</P>
<P>
Some people count the miles they run. Abel R. Kiviat counts the steps he takes. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't do walking, I don't take any exercise," he said, pride in his craggy 
voice. 
</P>
<P>
He's earned the right. At the age of 97, Kiviat is the oldest living Olympic 
medalist. He was nosed out of a gold medal in the 1912 Stockholm Games when a 
fast-finishing Englishman named A.N.S. Jackson took the 1,500-meter run in 
3:56.8. Kiviat's 3:56.9 barely held off U.S. teammate Norman Taber for the 
silver. 
</P>
<P>
Kiviat took some consolation -- but not much -- when the United States won the 
3,000-meter team event. He got a gold even though his time was not among the 
top three scoring times for the United States. 
</P>
<P>
Kiviat was at Essex Community College this week to help kick off Fitness Month 
and Older Americans Month on Senior Fitness Day, and to talk about his silver 
medal and his longevity. 
</P>
<P>
He is a monument to clean living. Well, relatively speaking, anyway. Aside from 
the glass of John Dewars scotch (on the rocks) and two Optimo Admiral cigars he 
allows himself each day, he has no other admitted vices. 
</P>
<P>
At the least, Kiviat, who turns 98 on June 23, is the product of good genes. 
The son of Russian immigrants, Abel has a sister still living who is 96 and a 
brother -- the baby in the family -- who is 86. His son, Arthur, will be 76 on 
Christmas Day. His mother lived to be 81, while his father died at the tender 
age of 66. 
</P>
<P>
"I've been lucky," Kiviat said several times during a two-hour reminisce. 
</P>
<P>
He wasn't kidding. He survived World War I as a buck private in a supply outfit 
in France. "Promoted three times," Kiviat remembered, "busted three times." 
</P>
<P>
One fateful night, he was scheduled to be in a threesome that drove ammunition 
to the front. He let another soldier go in his place, though. "He was an Irish 
boy," Kiviat said. "He made the suggestion (to switch)." 
</P>
<P>
The truck ran over a mine that night and all three people in it were killed. 
</P>
<P>
Asked to what he attributes his longevity, Kiviat repeats this litany: 
</P>
<P>
"I used no condiments. I got plenty of sleep. And I kept my nose clean, after I 
had it broken playing football and baseball." 
</P>
<P>
Although he says he was less than 5 feet tall and under 100 pounds at the time 
he competed in the 1912 Games, Kiviat was quite an athlete. He was an 
accomplished shortstop at Curtis High School in Staten Island, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
According to Glenn Kasper, who regularly accompanies Kiviat on speaking 
engagements as deputy director of the New Jersey Governor's Council on Physical 
Fitness &amp; Sports, Abel was being scouted by the Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
As the story goes, Kiviat got his start in track after winning a challenge race 
against a member of the Curtis track team. He became New York City's mile and 
880 champion as a prep runner, and then was invited by Lawson Robertson to join 
the Irish American Athletic Club. Kiviat was the only Jewish athlete on what he 
calls the "poor man's track club." 
</P>
<P>
According to Kasper, Kiviat went undefeated in every race he entered in 1911. 
He set a world record for the 1,500-meter run in the U.S. Olympic trials at 
Harvard Stadium in 1912, a record that stood until 1930. 
</P>
<P>
And he was favored to take the gold in Sweden. As the race was described in 
"The Story of the Olympic Games, 776 B.C. to 1964" by John Kieran and Arthur 
Daley, he took the lead in the bell lap and ran down the stretch with teammates 
Taber and John Paul Jones abreast of him. 
</P>
<P>
Great Britain's Jackson passed them all, however, on the final turn. 
</P>
<P>
"I remember it vividly," Kiviat said. "In fact, I had nightmares about it." 
</P>
<P>
There were no Olympics in 1916, and Kiviat didn't get around to competing again 
until 1924. At that point, his career effectively ended when he was asked to 
run the steeplechase in the trials. He promptly hit a hurdle, fell into the 
next water hole, and suffered a badly sprained ankle. 
</P>
<P>
Kiviat worked a number of jobs in the ensuing years -- he was a sporting goods 
salesman for Wanamaker's and worked in the New York Stock Exchange -- before 
settling in for 41 years with the government as a court clerk. He retired at 
age 71. Some eight years ago, Olympic historian Stan Saplan looked up the 
forgotten Kiviat and Abel has been making appearances ever since. 
</P>
<P>
In 1988, Kiviat, who had lost his Olympic medals, received replicas from the 
great grandson of the king of Sweden, who had initially given him the medals. 
In 1989, he met President Bush and was a torch bearer at the U.S. Olympic 
Festival in Oklahoma City. And, if all goes well, he will lead the U.S. Olympic 
delegation at the '92 Games in Barcelona. 
</P>
<P>
He will be 100 in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Profile; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA050690-0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 280383 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 6, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<P>
MARVIN LEVIN 
</P>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part A; Page 3; Column 1; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1678 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
NO SATISFACTION FOR INFORMANT IN CAPITOL STING; 
</P>
<P>
CORRUPTION: MAN WHO WENT UNDERCOVER FOR THE FBI IS UNHAPPY WITH THE PACE OF 
PROSECUTIONS. HE ALSO SAYS LEGISLATURE STILL HASN'T CLEANED UP ITS ACT. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PAUL JACOBS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It has been 20 months since the FBI raided the state Capitol and brought an end 
to its undercover political corruption probe, and Marv Levin is running out of 
patience. 
</P>
<P>
A private businessman who became a crucial government informant for more than 
three years in the elaborate federal sting operation, Levin says he is 
frustrated by the slow pace of prosecutions. And he is even more annoyed with 
the Legislature itself for what he sees as its failure to get its own house 
quickly in order. 
</P>
<P>
"I see the (legislative) games become more sophisticated," Levin told The Times 
in an interview that ended a year and a half of silence. "The old boys' network 
is alive and well, just doing things a little differently now." New ethics 
reform moving through the Legislature is a step in the right direction, he 
said, but only a step. 
</P>
<P>
Levin, who is 55 and not in the best of health, said he had hoped the system 
would change and that he is speaking out now because voters need to be told 
that it hasn't. 
</P>
<P>
He also believes the time has finally arrived when he can safely call attention 
to himself. He feels he has earned a brief moment in the light to explain how 
he risked financial ruin to help set right a political system that often favors 
those with the biggest checkbooks. 
</P>
<P>
It was Levin who helped the FBI write special-interest bills that would 
supposedly help a bogus company open a plant near Sacramento. It was Levin who 
advised undercover investigators posing as Southern businessmen on the 
intricacies of moving those bills through the Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
And it was Levin, wearing a concealed recording device, who acted as the 
go-between with legislative aides who saw to it that the measures were passed. 
</P>
<P>
More than six years after he began assisting the FBI -- and long after his 
direct role in the sting had ended -- he still wears an electronic pager given 
to him by the agents. The federal agents still beep occasionally. 
</P>
<P>
Throughout the undercover operation, Levin feared that the disclosure that he 
was a paid informant for the FBI could damage him and destroy the $600-million 
Lighthouse Marina project that he and his partners are developing on the 
Sacramento River. And once his role did become public four years later, he 
found that instead of being hailed as a hero, his personal integrity was being 
questioned. 
</P>
<P>
Many people believed "that you can't be involved in something like this unless 
you're a crook yourself," Levin explained. 
</P>
<P>
At one critical moment in 1988, it took a letter of commendation from the FBI 
to allay the suspicions of local government officials who were reviewing the 
marina development. 
</P>
<P>
Terry L. Knowles, who headed the FBI's Sacramento office, wrote in Levin's 
defense: "The personal sacrifice and time spent by you without consideration 
for your own personal well-being should serve as an example to the community." 
The marina was approved by West Sacramento officials. 
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, looking back at events, Levin wonders whether going undercover 
was worth the risk -- to his business, to his health, to his family. At one 
point, he even worried that some of those who were snared in the sting might 
try to exact their revenge on his children. 
</P>
<P>
"This has taken an enormous toll on me personally," Levin said. 
</P>
<P>
"I've had (legislative) members who wouldn't see me any more," he said. "There 
are several I thought of as friends, as acquaintances, who refuse to deal with 
me." 
</P>
<P>
The federal investigation has already led to the conviction on political 
corruption charges of Sen. Joseph B. Montoya (D-Whittier), who recently was 
sentenced to 6 1/2 years in federal prison. The probe has also resulted in 
similar charges being filed against State Board of Equalization member Paul 
Carpenter and a Montoya aide, and guilty pleas from a Republican legislative 
aide, a county sheriff and the sheriff's one-time top deputy. 
</P>
<P>
Levin describes himself as a reluctant participant in the federal investigation 
of political corruption. 
</P>
<P>
In 1984, he even approached a Republican assemblyman he knew, hoping that the 
lawmaker would agree to take his place in assisting federal agents. The 
legislator had long complained that something needed to be done about 
corruption. But he refused to help, Levin said. 
</P>
<P>
Later, the federal investigators brought in their own replacement, a one-time 
United Nations official from New York who had been convicted of fraud and was 
hoping to win a presidential pardon by acting as an undercover operative in the 
Sacramento investigation. 
</P>
<P>
"I thought, 'I'm out of it. I'm so happy,' " Levin said. "He was very 
distinguished-looking. He wore glasses. He was well dressed. He had all the 
things I didn't have. He smelled of wealth. . . . This was someone who really 
looked and played the part." 
</P>
<P>
Levin hoped that he would be able to stay in the background, playing a strictly 
advisory role for the FBI while the New Yorker would be the one to make the 
direct contacts and secretly record his conversations. 
</P>
<P>
But ultimately the federal authorities decided they could not use the outsider 
because his criminal record could prove to be a problem when prosecutors took 
their cases to court, according to Levin. (This and other details of Levin's 
account were confirmed by sources familiar with the investigation.) 
</P>
<P>
Levin had a number of contacts in the Legislature because of his past jobs as a 
consultant-lobbyist with a nonprofit small business development corporation and 
as an official with the state office of small business development. 
</P>
<P>
"I wanted to get the sting going, but I really didn't want to be part of it," 
Levin said. 
</P>
<P>
Finally, the agent in charge of the FBI probe -- a friend whose son had 
sometimes played in a neighborhood park with Levin's children -- said that the 
only way for the investigation to succeed was if Levin would agree to go 
undercover. 
</P>
<P>
"He said, 'If you don't do it, we can't go forward. There is no alternative,' " 
Levin said. "He hit me between the eyes. 'You're the one bitching about our not 
doing anything. Others have refused (to cooperate). Are you going to do the 
same?' " 
</P>
<P>
With considerable trepidation, Levin agreed to go ahead. 
</P>
<P>
It wasn't the first time that Levin had agreed to wear a wire for the local 
office of the FBI. A few years before the Capitol sting, Levin had told local 
FBI agents about a fishy business deal that had been offered to him involving 
an official of the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development. He ended 
up with an FBI tape recorder stuffed inside a new pair of $200 cowboy boots he 
had bought for the occasion. 
</P>
<P>
When the federal authorities began the preliminary work on the sting in 1984, 
the FBI paid Levin $1,800 a month for almost a year, while he was pretending to 
be a consultant for Gulf Shrimp Fisheries Inc. of Mobile, Ala. The phony 
company was supposedly seeking state help in setting up a shrimp processing 
plant near Sacramento. 
</P>
<P>
The federal investigators supplied Levin with a set of fake correspondence from 
John E. (Jack) Gordon -- on paper, the president of Gulf Shrimp, but in reality 
an undercover FBI agent. On one of the letters to Levin, intended to be flashed 
at legislative staff members and legislators if the authenticity of the company 
was questioned, Gordon scrawled a handwritten note to Levin: "You could make 
some money too!" 
</P>
<P>
Levin helped the phony firm secure a $100,000 loan from a nonprofit agency 
headed by a former legislative aide, Darryl O. Freeman. 
</P>
<P>
Then Levin, who had once been a lobbyist and consultant for the California 
Rural Small Business Development Corp., helped the agents craft a narrow bill 
that would supposedly benefit Gulf Shrimp, but not any other company. 
</P>
<P>
To help move the sting bill, carried by Assemblywoman Gwen Moore (D-Los 
Angeles), through the Senate, Levin turned to an old acquaintance, legislative 
aide John Shahabian. Levin introduced Shahabian to Gulf Shrimp's "Jack Gordon." 
Shahabian told Gordon that it would cost $20,000 to win passage of the shrimp 
bill -- money that went into the campaign coffers of Carpenter, then a state 
senator. The measure passed in 1986 but was vetoed by Gov. George Deukmejian, 
who had been tipped off about the FBI sting. 
</P>
<P>
A year later, Levin aided federal investigators in an effort to turn Shahabian 
into an undercover informant. 
</P>
<P>
Levin said the FBI brought in a two-man "psych team" to help figure out the 
best way to approach Shahabian. Levin said the bureau's human behavior experts 
believed that Shahabian's close ties to his family made it likely he would 
agree to cooperate. 
</P>
<P>
Frightened by the prospect of going to prison, Shahabian agreed to help the 
federal probe with a second sting bill, and for more than a year, he too led a 
double life as an undercover operative. 
</P>
<P>
Levin said he has some regrets about bringing Shahabian into the sting. 
Although the former legislative aide was granted immunity from prosecution 
because of his cooperation with the FBI, he eventually lost his Senate job. 
</P>
<P>
But Levin is also convinced he did the right thing, despite the misgivings. 
</P>
<P>
During one particularly low moment in 1987 -- just before the FBI persuaded 
Shahabian to cooperate -- Levin wrote a long letter to the agent he had 
befriended almost a decade before. "I became involved because I was enraged 
with a political system that had one standard for money and power and another 
for everyone else," Levin wrote. "I still don't personally think that what 
happens as a result of your effort will cause substantive change. However, I 
don't think I have a right to complain unless I am willing to act for change 
when given the opportunity." 
</P>
<P>
A year later, Levin had become a kind of fugitive, taking a cruise to escape a 
burst of press attention after the FBI raid. 
</P>
<P>
From aboard ship, his pulse racing and his blood pressure high, he wrote his 
friend at the FBI: "The reason so few people step forward to help is that the 
price of helping is very high. . . . Would I do it again? Probably, although I 
don't know whether I could physically take it. I would do it because one has to 
believe in something and stand up for your beliefs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Marv Levin Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
